description.text:
The Firefly board game takes up a lot of space. This caddy will help players keep their ships organized. It has slots for Upgrades, Jobs and Cargo. There's even additional Cargo and Stash slots, in case the player gets an upgrade later on.
The oval space in the lower left is for a badge sticker. It should fit these labels: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000UCT95K/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 (1 3/4 X 3 3/4" Oval Silver Foil Labels).
Enjoy, and keep flying.

If your build plate is large enough, you should be able to print this flat, one at a time. However, I recommend printing it oriented so that the upgrade slots are at the bottom and touching the build plate, that way, if there is a little curling, the functionality won't be affected. You'll still be able to get your cards into the upgrade slots. You will also be able to print more than one at a time.
If you are printing on a slightly smaller build plate (like a Replicator 2X), you will have to print one at a time and Rotate on the Z axis to get the model to fit on the build plate.
There is enough tolerance to account for PLA shrinking. But if you are printing with ABS, you may have to adjust scaling a bit. If you print this in ABS, please comment on how it went.

7/10/2017 Added a second version with:
  • Two more card slots and no emblem space
  • Changed orientation; so you can print it the way it loads in your slicer
  • Reduced width

comments.text:
By the way, I reduced the BOM a bit, using a slightly different assembly:
No washers, instead I increased the rim around the ball bearings a bit. To fix the ball bearings in place, I printed 4 plugs, tightly fitting the holder axle bores. These plugs I pushed through bore on one side, the ball bearing, and the bore on the other side, using casing tongs, top end first, Reason: By also increasing bed temperature when printing those plugs, I made them to elephant foot very slightly. Idea was that this serves as an end stop of the plug on one side, but those plugs sit so tightly that this wasn't needed. Still, as the bottom plug ends (the print base layer end) still has a slightly increased diameters, that end is harder to push through the bores.
Therefore, besides ball bearings and holder base, only those 4 plugs were used, and no additional material needed. To avoid an overly thick rim (which needs to protrude over the outer ball bearings perimeter, I used smaller ones (688z, 8x16x5mm).

remixed_from.title: Sliced Human Skull with Mandible and Teeth

description.text: I hollowed the skull out in Meshmixer and performed the trephination and did the final touchup in 3dCoat. The print is done in white PLA on our SeeMeCNC Orion. White PLA sometimes gets scuffed and discolored when sanded, and here it works to our advantage. After sanding the obvious layer lines away the model didn't look much like a 3d print anymore. I painted it with a couple coats of yellowish brownish acrylic paint and wiped the paint back before it dried completely. After this treatment it was downright creepy. It is a good size for drinking tea out of your enemy's skull. If you want to drink mead you might want to size it up a little. The small size actually makes it extra creepy because it appears to be the skull of a child, or a leprechaun, or a sinister homonculus of some kind. We talked about this thing and a whole lot more about 3d printing on the 3D Printing Today podcast available on iTunes, Stitcher radio or direct from the source at http://threedprintingtoday.libsyn.com/

N scale flat car for truly heavy loads; based on the GEX 80000.
This car is huge, just like the real thing, you will get to spend plenty of time shuffling it around your layout trying to avoid problems with overhang on curves. You must either weight the car or build a load with some heft to keep it on the rails. There is a generator included, it will work if you fill it with BBs.
Uses 8 (!) Intermountain trucks.
Updated the lower bolsters to provide a bit easier railing and better side to side stability,

title: Feet for Printrbot Simple Metal Version 2

description.text: Everything is better with more polygons!  I wanted to reprint my printrbot feet in black, but why not change up the design a little first?  This time, the back feet snap on (with a great deal of force) and won't be coming off any time soon.  The front feet slip into place as before, but now I've added a post with an attachable clip so it hooks onto the top of the printer base.  In short, you can now pick up the printer and move it about without losing the feet.

I use self-adhesive rubber pads (with a little glue for good measure) underneath the feet to provide shock absorption and friction so it doesn't slide off the table.  
To attach the back feet, place one underneath it's corner (they are NOT interchangeable) and then press down very hard.  You want the bolt head to push past the plastic and snap into it's corresponding hole.  
For the front feet, slip the base on first, and then apply a couple drops of super glue to the hole on top of the post.  Then slip the clip into place.

title: RODAMIENTO LINEAL lm8uu casero con virolas de 5/16´´

description.text:
Rodamiento lineal LM8UU casero con virolas de gas de 5/16´´ .
con muy buen deslizamiento y casi sin ruido si se lo lubrica bien. ya que es rose de metal con metal.

INSTRUCCIONES:
1). Tomar las virolas de gas de 5/16´´(pulgadas) y verificar que entren en la varilla, de no entrar agarrar una lima cola de ratón, limar un poco el interior hasta eliminar rebaba y que pasen sin problema alguno. Segunda opción(si sigue sin pasar): agarre una mecha de métrica 8 y pase la con la mano por la virola.
2). Luego de imprimir la pieza lime con la lima el interior y rebabas plásticas hasta que pase sin problemas por la varilla.
3). Coloque una virola de cada lado y haga presión contra una superficie plana si lo requiere la situación, hasta que encajen estas. NOTA: si es necesario o quiere usted, ponga un poco de la gotita(pegamento) en el diámetro externo de la virola para que se pegue al tubo plástico, ¡CON MUCHO CUIDADO!
4). Ponga grasa amarilla o lubricante en la varilla e introduzca el rodamiento casero con cuidado y desplace hasta que tenga un buen movimiento.
Con esto queda terminado el rodamiento casero para que use en cualquier parte de la impresora 3d o en otros proyectos.
Nota: la virola al ser de 5/16´´ tiene un diámetro interno mayor o menor a 7,93 mm y su varilla es de +-8mm, por lo cual se debe probar primero en la varilla y seguir los pasos desde el principio.

title: Cube callibration test (added highres and 1cm versions)

description.text:
This allows you to quickly callibrate your new 3d printer be it reprap, printrbot or whatnot. It's a 2cm cube with a 1cm hole along the x-ax. Just added a highres version so the hole is more circular and it's centered.
Also added the openscad file for this and a 1cm version with 5mm hole for printing at 0.1 layers this one is a good test... The original file is a smaller download so kept it...

Print at 100% is around 10min. It slices really quickly allowing you to do fast iterations.
Once you got the z-ax properly callibrated and your infill etc. You can print at 500% and pause the print after the first perimeter -> it should be exactly 10cm by 10cm then and you can measure + adjust your x and y steps properly. Anyway it's the fastest way I found to get a printer fully callibrated nicely ;). Did this in openscad but lost that file ... only uploaded the stl here...

title: LED Ring Snap Mount for Rostock MAX

description.text:
This mount is designed to snap to a SeeMeCNC Rostock MAX or Orion effector with no fasteners except for zip ties. Its purpose is to stand off an LED ring from the bottom of the effector, so it doesn't ride up against the universal joints and possibly cause "delta arm blues" type issues. (It also gives the LED ring a more finished looking mount.)
.
You can get the LED rings here, two for under ten bucks:
http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B006W2EKHE/ref=wms_ohs_product_img?ie=UTF8&psc=1
.
The three protruding jaws that snap the mount to the effector platform are a little delicate, so be careful. After fitting the mount, push up near the jaws so that the part fits securely to the effector with no gap.
.
IMPORTANT: Ensure that the mount fits securely, with no slop or wiggle room. It fits perfectly on my machine, but that's with my calibration and the particular filament I used. This does not guarantee it will be a perfect fit on your machine. The mount must not fall during a print. If it does, mechanical, electronic, or fire damage may ensue. For extra security, it can be lashed to the effector.
.
If you're using my E3D mount to affix an E3D or other groovemount hot end to the bottom of your effector, note that the snap mount has three recesses to match the profile of the E3D mount. That way, when you fit it, it won't be bent out of shape.
.
That done, secure the LED ring to the mount with zip ties. Use at least four, and tighten them down well. The LED ring's wires will be clamped between the mount and the LED ring at the point where they're soldered, which should prevent the solder joints from working lose and failing over time. I recommend putting one of the zip ties close to the solder joints.

The idea of a Tri-Copter is for more helicopter like flying and better yaw performance and this was what I was after (I already have a 200QX, see my other posting). I love flying this Copter. It flows through the air and is fast (if you want). Looking through ThingiVerse I came across the one by Kezat and decided to elaborate on that design since the design of the arms and attachment method was unique. This one takes the Y and makes it a T plus provides a Cap to protect the electronics and gives a place for the receiver to hang. I also designed legs to land on which also reinforces the arm and body connection. Last two items is the mounting of the motors was sized up for the sunny sky 2204s 2300kv motors (hover at below half throttle), and the servo deck is underneath the tail and designed for a 9g servo (TGY-9025MG is what I am using). Balance is spot on with a 3s 650 battery hanging below the electronics using a velcro strap. (7 minute flights)
I used 4lb fishing line on both sides of the servo (Push - Pull) to connect the servo arm to the motor mount arms.
I have also included the MultiWii screen for the PID values v2.1 (I fly MutliWii). It flies amazing. 1-28-2016 - Just added a main frame that will mount a Naze32 Bd. What will follow shortly will be another top plate that will allow the mounting of an FPV camera, Video Transmitter, Servo for auto tilting of the FPV camera by the Naze32 Bd (or manually through an extra ch and slider). The CC3D will also fit, but I suggest the Naze32 as it is better supported for Tri-copters. 12-28-2014 - Updated the bottom plate with reinforced mounting holes and re-uploaded the tail with .stl's that contain no manifold errors. Been flying hard, spectacular crashes, no broken plastic, .... just broken zip-ties as it was designed. 11-27-2014 - Happy Thanksgiving! I upgraded the tail boom and thickened the top and bottom by 1mm each to strengthen it against those ooooops moments. The tie wraps are suppose to break not the tail boom itself. I also print the tail boom @ 100% infill. Enjoy. 11-1-2014 - Added a bottom plate so your wiring can move down instead of sitting directly below your controller board and to give a smoother place to hang your battery. 10-26-2014 - Updated the body to reinforce the tail section from the occasional oooops. Improved the Arm Clamp Plate to allow the arms to "pull" into the mount points better. Added side bars to the mount points to stabilize the side to side arm movement. 9-28-2014 - To each his own, I downgraded to 2.1 until I can figure out better settings for 2.3. I get better dynamic range on my stick movement with 2.1 plus in level mode it won't try and flip if you go past 3/4 stick. Take it out of level mode and it flips over in a second. The PID settings shown are for 2.1 and not 2.3. Also added a new part to clamp the tops of the arms to keep them from flexing up with anything less then an absolutely tight zip tie. Right now the compass in the multiwii is to close to the motors and does not work well with the interference. I'll be trying some longer arms soon. Please give me feedback in the comments on your setup and findings. Enjoy. 9-26-2014 - This tri is amazing fun. Sounds like a Formula 1 racer when you rip through the sky screaming across the horizon. it's fast, it's agile, it carries FPV gear will little effort. I'll be updating the FPV capabilities soon with extra trays. Print the tail out at 90% fill for strength. The rest of the parts have been printed at 40% for lightness. The arms have proven plenty strong at 40% fill. If you use the tgy-9025, you will need to reverse the servo direction in the software (if you are using multiwii). I have since upgraded to ver 2.3 from ver 2.1 and it is incredibly responsive. Not in level/horizon mode I have successfully flipped it end over and it pulls that off smoothly. 9-13-2014 - Bumped up the rate on the Yaw (rudder/tail servo) to get more hell like response (that's why we build a tri). Also been playing with the alt hold (BARO) and Level settings (ACC) to trim these out. Raining today so not much test flying; should be good tomorrow. New settings are reflected in the revised MultiWii Config image.

This snake-like, flexible cable conduit allows you to secure loose cables on the floor from being tripped over. I prefer this to taping cables to the ground, which leads to sticky smear on cables and floor over time.
You can print as many modules as necessary, each one adds around 45mm to the whole conduit. The modules can be clicked together and, als long as the conduit is flat on the ground, stick together quite reliably. Need more conduit? Print more modules!
The flexible side parts allow you to push in the cables from the side, module by module, without need to fiddle around and push them in from one end.
The snakey cable conduit can be stepped on, as the construction is quite crush-resistant, of course depending on the material you use. With the right choice of material, it withstands a casual step without problems. And, if one module beaks, you can always replace it with a newly printed one. Hint: don't print it in white.
Works well even when printed in low resolution. Don't forget to secure the »female« end of the whole chaine with the end piece, as this adds neccessary support when stepped on.
